<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Characterization-of-the-baobab-tree-fruit-and-study-of-its-processing-into-nectar" title="Characterization of the baobab tree fruit and study of its processing into nectar" alt="link">Characterization of the baobab tree fruit and study of its processing into nectar</a></h2>

	
					<p>
Title: Characterization of the baobab tree fruit and study of its processing into nectar
Author: M. Cissé, M. Sakho, M. Dornier, C. Mar Diop, M. Reynes and O. Sock
Source: <i>Fruits </i>64: (1) 19-34Date: 2009
 The baobab (<i>Adansonia digitata L</i>.) is a tree that grows wild in Senegal, where the fruit is consumed in various forms. If the ecology and botany of plants have been well studied, work on the transformation of fruit or the impact of processing treatments on the quality of the finished products is rare. To assess the technological potential of the processing treatment for these fruits, prior to the development of their transformation products in local, regional and international markets, we sought to characterize the raw material (biochemical composition and nutritional quality), and to study the product that produces nectar.</p>
							<p><span class="date">11/01/2011</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Characterization-of-the-baobab-tree-fruit-and-study-of-its-processing-into-nectar">Read more...</a>
