						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Postharvest-treatment-of-sorghum-Sorghum-bicolor-in-Botswana" title="Postharvest treatment of sorghum (Sorghum bicolor) in Botswana" alt="link">Postharvest treatment of sorghum (Sorghum bicolor) in Botswana</a></h2>

	
					<p>
Title: Postharvest treatment of sorghum (Sorghum bicolor) in Botswana 
Author: C. Mogkoko
Source: CGIAR FoodNetDate: 2001Sorghum (Sorghum bicolor) is undoubtedly the staple cereal of Botswana and is grown widely in the country. Eisener et al. (1982) reported statistics of surveys conducted in the Southern and Southeastern districts of Botswana, in which 96% of the respondents indicate that they eat sorghum. In another study reported by IICT (1997), conducted in Northeastern Botswana, 52% of the respondents ate sorghum-based foods every day. Several varieties of sorghum and millet, both indigenous and exotic, are grown in the country. All these varieties have proved to be of good food value, and may be used for different industrial applications. The development of these varieties, and their subsequent use, has been steered by a number of institutions in the country and abroad, notably, the Ministry of Agriculture, SADC/ICRISAT, THE Botswana Technology Centre (and its international collaborators-CIRAD, NRI AND IICT), and others. An identified constraint that continues to hinder the national objective of food security is postproduction losses. These losses are believed to be high in magnitude although there is no loss assessment studies carried out in the country. These losses are caused by a number of agents, mainly insects and postproduction practices. This paper seeks to examine post harvest treatments of sorghum and highlight the challenges and opportunities facing the crop post harvest.</p>
							<p><span class="date">11/01/2011</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Postharvest-treatment-of-sorghum-Sorghum-bicolor-in-Botswana">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Post-Harvest-Apple-Practises-in-South-Africa" title="Post Harvest Apple Practises in South Africa" alt="link">Post Harvest Apple Practises in South Africa</a></h2>

	
					<p>
Title: Post Harvest Apple Practises in South Africa
Author: I. Crouch
Source: Washington Tree Fruit Postharvest ConferenceDate: December 2003South Africa currently has over 22,500 hectares under apple production. The main apple growing areas are in the Western Cape with some recent plantings of Royal Gala in the Orange Free State. Over 18 million cartons of apples are exported from South Africa each year to the United Kingdom (39%), Central Europe (23%), Middle and Far East (24%), Africa (11%) and the Americas (3%). Apples constitute 30% of the total deciduous crop in South Africa. Apples have been grown in South Africa since 1652, when Jan van Riebeeck established the first plantings. Good post harvest practices have arisen from the need to continually improve quality to meet more and more stringent market requirements. It is imperative to maintain these high standards from the time the fruit is harvested until it is sold.</p>
							<p><span class="date">11/01/2011</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Post-Harvest-Apple-Practises-in-South-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Extension-of-shelf-life-and-control-of-human-pathogens-in-produce-by-antimicrobial-edible-films-and-coatings" title="Extension of shelf life and control of human pathogens in produce by antimicrobial edible films and coatings" alt="link">Extension of shelf life and control of human pathogens in produce by antimicrobial edible films and coatings</a></h2>

	
					<p>
Title: Extension of shelf life and control of human pathogens in produce by antimicrobial edible films and coatings
Author: T.H. McHugh, R.J. Avena-Bustillos, Wen-Xian Du
Source: <a href="http://eu.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0813804167,descCd-google_preview.html" target="_blank">Microbial safety of fresh produce / Xuetong Fan ... [et al.], eds. Wiley-Blackwell, p. 225-239</a>Date: 2009The use of edible films and coatings as carriers of natural antimicrobials (such as plant essential oils) constitutes an approach for external protection of fruits and vegetables to reduce surface microbial populations and to enhance oxygen-barrier properties, potentially increasing food safety as well as shelf life of highly perishable foods such as fresh and fresh-cut fruits and vegetables. Appropriately formulated edible films and coatings can be utilized for fresh produce to meet challenges associated with stable quality, market safety, nutritional value, and economic production cost.</p>
							<p><span class="date">11/01/2011</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Extension-of-shelf-life-and-control-of-human-pathogens-in-produce-by-antimicrobial-edible-films-and-coatings">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Effect-of-edible-coatings-on-the-shelf-life-of-in-natura-guava-Psidium-guajava-L.-stored-under-refrigeration" title="Effect of edible coatings on the shelf life of in natura guava (Psidium guajava L.) stored under refrigeration" alt="link">Effect of edible coatings on the shelf life of in natura guava (Psidium guajava L.) stored under refrigeration</a></h2>

	
					<p>
Title: Effect of edible coatings on the shelf life of in natura guava (Psidium guajava L.) stored under refrigeration
Author: F.M. Fakhouri, C. Grosso
Source: <i>Braz. J. Food Technol</i>. 6: (2) 203-211Date: 2003Filmogenic coatings produced with gelatin, triacetin and lauric acid were applied to white guava fruits during the mature green stage. The fruits were stored under refrigeration for twenty days, together with an uncoated control. The physiochemical characteristics used to evaluate maturation included pH, titratable acidity, °Brix, total and reducing sugars, hardness, colour and loss in weight, and were measured at four-day intervals. In addition the shelf life was evaluated by a sensory analysis, including overall appearance, shine, color and buying intention at the same intervals. A specific sensory analysis for flavour, aroma, texture and buying intention was applied after 9 days of storage. The coatings were shown to be effective in extending the shelf life of the guavas as compared to the uncoated fruits, and were well accepted by the consumers throughout the whole period of the experiment and also in the specific sensory analyses. Of the coatings studied, the gelatin film containing triacetin was shown to be the best, both from the sensory and physicochemical characteristics studied. The incorporation of brightness due to the use of coatings had a favourable effect on the appearance. Coatings containing lauric acid, despite some positive aspects, influenced the typical flavour of the guavas. However, washing of the fruits before eating was sufficient to remove the off-flavour.</p>
							<p><span class="date">11/01/2011</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Effect-of-edible-coatings-on-the-shelf-life-of-in-natura-guava-Psidium-guajava-L.-stored-under-refrigeration">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Manual-for-the-preparation-and-sale-of-fruits-and-vegetables.-From-field-to-market" title="Manual for the preparation and sale of fruits and vegetables. From field to market" alt="link">Manual for the preparation and sale of fruits and vegetables. From field to market</a></h2>

	
					<p>
Title: Manual for the preparation and sale of fruits and vegetables. From field to market
Author: A.F. López Camelo 
Source: FAODate: 2004The fruit and vegetable production sector of Latin America and the Caribbean, Asia and Eastern Europe is facing a new situation where, on the one hand, supermarket chains account for an increasing percentage of the domestic food retail market and, on the other hand, producers must compete in an increasingly demanding global market for non- traditional and off-season fruits and vegetables. Producers with the necessary financial, management and technological skills are already meeting the new challenges; however, small farmers are increasingly being marginalized and will be facing unequal market conditions unless they are able to change their practices to meet the needs of a modern food marketing system. Regardless of the production system, the technological challenge is to increase returns through the rational use of available resources, reducing production costs and post-harvest losses, enhancing competitiveness and adding value to the final product. On the basis of these principles, this manual analyses the techniques for reducing post-harvest losses and ensuring quality and food safety from harvest to consumption. The new concept of quality involves ensuring total quality for increasing competitiveness and providing produce that better satisfies the demands of food retailers and, ultimately, the consumers.</p>
							<p><span class="date">11/01/2011</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Manual-for-the-preparation-and-sale-of-fruits-and-vegetables.-From-field-to-market">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/An-Introduction-to-the-Physiology-and-Handling-of-Fruit-Vegetables-and-Ornamentals" title="An Introduction to the Physiology and Handling of Fruit, Vegetables and Ornamentals" alt="link">An Introduction to the Physiology and Handling of Fruit, Vegetables and Ornamentals</a></h2>

	
					<p>
Postharvest: An Introduction to the Physiology and Handling of Fruit, Vegetables and Ornamentals
Author: R. Wills, W.B. McGlasson, D. Graham and D. Joyce (Editors)Date: 1998These three books provide a wealth of information ranging from research aspects to the application of technologies developed for the successful postharvest handling and storage of a wide range of horticultural commodities, both temperate and subtropical in origin.</p>
							<p><span class="date">11/01/2011</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/An-Introduction-to-the-Physiology-and-Handling-of-Fruit-Vegetables-and-Ornamentals">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Africa-Simple-food-processing-techniques-increases-farmers-incomes" title="Africa: Simple food processing techniques increases farmers' incomes" alt="document">Africa: Simple food processing techniques increases farmers' incomes</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> How training in simple food processing techniques can help village farmers successfully increase their incomes and improve the nutritional status of their families is described using the case of the Integration of Tree Crops into Farming Systems Project (ITFSP). The ITFSP is a regional project with activities in Kenya, Malawi, Tanzania, Uganda and Zimbabwe. In 1995, the project chose Kitui District, Kenya, as a pilot area because farmers had indicated that they had difficulties marketing fresh fruit and that a large part of the mango harvest rotted in their gardens. The main techniques introduced were wooden solar dryers, and jam and juice making. Local artisans were contracted to produce the dryers. In only 2 years, ITFSP has reached out to 27 farmer groups with a total membership of 680 farmers. A cost-benefit analysis of mango drying was performed using a variable number of drying days. The variation in gross margins per working day during the 1996/1997 season was assessed. Generally, the marketing of products is greatly enhanced when producer and marketing associations are formed.</p>
							<p><span class="date">28/06/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Reducing-Postharvest-Losses-A-Challenge-for-the-Scientific-Community/Relevant-publications/Africa-Simple-food-processing-techniques-increases-farmers-incomes">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl"/>
<p>

